# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-key-vault
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In cryptography, a **certificate authority** or **certification authority** (**CA**) is an entity that stores, signs, and issues digital certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made about the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] A CA acts as a trusted third party—trusted both by the subject (owner) of the certificate and by the party relying upon the certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The format of these certificates is specified by the X.509 or EMV standard.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] One particularly common use for certificate authorities is to sign certificates used in HTTPS, the secure browsing protocol for the World Wide Web.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Another common use is in issuing identity cards by national governments for use in electronically signing documents.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Trusted certificates can be used to create secure connections to a server via the Internet.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] A certificate is essential in order to circumvent a malicious party which happens to be on the route to a target server which acts as if it were the target.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Such a scenario is commonly referred to as a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The client uses the CA certificate to authenticate the CA signature on the server certificate, as part of the authorizations before launching a secure connection.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Usually, client software—for example, browsers—include a set of trusted CA certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This makes sense, as many users need to trust their client software.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] A malicious or compromised client can skip any security check and still fool its users into believing otherwise.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The clients of a CA are server supervisors who call for a certificate that their servers will bestow to users.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Commercial CAs charge money to issue certificates, and their customers anticipate the CA's certificate to be contained within the majority of web browsers, so that safe connections to the certified servers work efficiently out-of-the-box.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The quantity of web browsers, other devices, and applications which trust a particular certificate authority is referred to as ubiquity.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Mozilla, which is a non-profit business, issues several commercial CA certificates with its products.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] While Mozilla developed their own policy, the CA/Browser Forum developed similar guidelines for CA trust.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] A single CA certificate may be shared among multiple CAs or their resellers.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] A *root* CA certificate may be the base to issue multiple *intermediate* CA certificates with varying validation requirements.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In addition to commercial CAs, some non-profits issue publicly-trusted digital certificates without charge, for example Let's Encrypt.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Some large cloud computing and web hosting companies are also publicly-trusted CAs and issue certificates to services hosted on their infrastructure, for example IBM Cloud, Amazon Web Services, Cloudflare, and Google Cloud Platform.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Large organizations or government bodies may have their own PKIs (public key infrastructure), each containing their own CAs.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Any site using self-signed certificates acts as its own CA.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Each payment card presents along with its card data also the Card Issuer Certificate to the POS.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The Issuer Certificate is signed by EMV CA Certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The POS retrieves the public key of EMV CA from its storage, validates the Issuer Certificate and authenticity of the payment card before sending the payment request to the payment scheme.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Browsers and other clients of sorts characteristically allow users to add or do away with CA certificates at will.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] While server certificates regularly last for a relatively short period, CA certificates are further extended, so, for repeatedly visited servers, it is less error-prone importing and trusting the CA issued, rather than confirm a security exemption each time the server's certificate is renewed.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Less often, trustworthy certificates are used for encrypting or signing messages.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] CAs dispense end-user certificates too, which can be used with S/MIME.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] However, encryption entails the receiver's public key and, since authors and receivers of encrypted messages, apparently, know one another, the usefulness of a trusted third party remains confined to the signature verification of messages sent to public mailing lists.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Worldwide, the certificate authority business is fragmented, with national or regional providers dominating their home market.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This is because many uses of digital certificates, such as for legally binding digital signatures, are linked to local law, regulations, and accreditation schemes for certificate authorities.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] However, the market for globally trusted TLS/SSL server certificates is largely held by a small number of multinational companies.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This market has significant barriers to entry due to the technical requirements.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] While not legally required, new providers may choose to undergo annual security audits (such as WebTrust for certificate authorities in North America and ETSI in Europe) to be included as a trusted root by a web browser or operating system.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] As of 24 August 2020, 147 root certificates, representing 52 organizations, are trusted in the Mozilla Firefox web browser, 168 root certificates, representing 60 organizations, are trusted by macOS, and 255 root certificates, representing 101 organizations, are trusted by Microsoft Windows.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] As of Android 4.2 (Jelly Bean), Android currently contains over 100 CAs that are updated with each release.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Let's Encrypt is operated by the newly formed Internet Security Research Group, a California nonprofit recognized as federally tax-exempt.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The top spot has been held by Symantec (or VeriSign before it was purchased by Symantec) ever since [our] survey began, with it currently accounting for just under a third of all certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] As of July 2024 the survey company W3Techs, which collects statistics on certificate authority usage among the Alexa top 10 million and the Tranco top 1 million websites, lists the five largest authorities by absolute usage share as below.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The commercial CAs that issue the bulk of certificates for HTTPS servers typically use a technique called "domain validation" to authenticate the recipient of the certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The techniques used for domain validation vary between CAs, but in general domain validation techniques are meant to prove that the certificate applicant controls a given domain name, not any information about the applicant's identity.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Many Certificate Authorities also offer Extended Validation (EV) certificates as a more rigorous alternative to domain validated certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Extended validation is intended to verify not only control of a domain name, but additional identity information to be included in the certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Some browsers display this additional identity information in a green box in the URL bar.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Domain validation suffers from certain structural security limitations.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In particular, it is always vulnerable to attacks that allow an adversary to observe the domain validation probes that CAs send.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] These can include attacks against the DNS, TCP, or BGP protocols (which lack the cryptographic protections of TLS/SSL), or the compromise of routers.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Such attacks are possible either on the network near a CA, or near the victim domain itself.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] One of the most common domain validation techniques involves sending an email containing an authentication token or link to an email address that is likely to be administratively responsible for the domain.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This could be the technical contact email address listed in the domain's WHOIS entry, or an administrative email like admin@, administrator@, webmaster@, hostmaster@ or postmaster@ the domain.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Some Certificate Authorities may accept confirmation using root@, info@, or support@ in the domain.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The theory behind domain validation is that only the legitimate owner of a domain would be able to read emails sent to these administrative addresses.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Domain validation implementations have sometimes been a source of security vulnerabilities.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In one instance, security researchers showed that attackers could obtain certificates for webmail sites because a CA was willing to use an email address like ssladmin@domain.com for domain.com, but not all webmail systems had reserved the "ssladmin" username to prevent attackers from registering it.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Prior to 2011, there was no standard list of email addresses that could be used for domain validation, so it was not clear to email administrators which addresses needed to be reserved.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The first version of the CA/Browser Forum Baseline Requirements, adopted November 2011, specified a list of such addresses.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This allowed mail hosts to reserve those addresses for administrative use, though such precautions are still not universal.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In January 2015, a Finnish man registered the username "hostmaster" at the Finnish version of Microsoft Live and was able to obtain a domain-validated certificate for live.fi, despite not being the owner of the domain name.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] A CA issues digital certificates that contain a public key and the identity of the owner.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The matching private key is not made available publicly, but kept secret by the end user who generated the key pair.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The certificate is also a confirmation or validation by the CA that the public key contained in the certificate belongs to the person, organization, server or other entity noted in the certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] A CA's obligation in such schemes is to verify an applicant's credentials, so that users and relying parties can trust the information in the issued certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] CAs use a variety of standards and tests to do so.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In essence, the certificate authority is responsible for saying "yes, this person is who they say they are, and we, the CA, certify that".
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] If the user trusts the CA and can verify the CA's signature, then they can also assume that a certain public key does indeed belong to whoever is identified in the certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Public-key cryptography can be used to encrypt data communicated between two parties.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This can typically happen when a user logs on to any site that implements the HTTP Secure protocol.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In this example let us suppose that the user logs on to their bank's homepage www.bank.example to do online banking.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] When the user opens www.bank.example homepage, they receive a public key along with all the data that their web-browser displays.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The rest of the communication then proceeds using the new (disposable) symmetric key, so when the user enters some information to the bank's page and submits the page (sends the information back to the bank) then the data the user has entered to the page will be encrypted by their web browser.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Therefore, even if someone can access the (encrypted) data that was communicated from the user to www.bank.example, such eavesdropper cannot read or decipher it.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This mechanism is only safe if the user can be sure that it is the bank that they see in their web browser.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] If the user types in www.bank.example, but their communication is hijacked and a fake website (that pretends to be the bank website) sends the page information back to the user's browser, the fake web-page can send a fake public key to the user (for which the fake site owns a matching private key).
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The user will fill the form with their personal data and will submit the page.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The fake web-page will then get access to the user's data.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This is what the certificate authority mechanism is intended to prevent.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] A certificate authority (CA) is an organization that stores public keys and their owners, and every party in a communication trusts this organization (and knows its public key).
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] When the user's web browser receives the public key from www.bank.example it also receives a digital signature of the key (with some more information, in a so-called X.509 certificate).
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The browser already possesses the public key of the CA and consequently can verify the signature, trust the certificate and the public key in it: since www.bank.example uses a public key that the certification authority certifies, a fake www.bank.example can only use the same public key.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Since the fake www.bank.example does not know the corresponding private key, it cannot create the signature needed to verify its authenticity.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] It is difficult to assure correctness of match between data and entity when the data are presented to the CA (perhaps over an electronic network), and when the credentials of the person/company/program asking for a certificate are likewise presented.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This is why commercial CAs often use a combination of authentication techniques including leveraging government bureaus, the payment infrastructure, third parties' databases and services, and custom heuristics.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In some enterprise systems, local forms of authentication such as Kerberos can be used to obtain a certificate which can in turn be used by external relying parties.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Notaries are required in some cases to personally know the party whose signature is being notarized; this is a higher standard than is reached by many CAs.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] 2. a contract relating to such transaction may not be denied legal effect, validity or enforceability solely because an electronic signature or electronic record was used in its formation.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Despite the security measures undertaken to correctly verify the identities of people and companies, there is a risk of a single CA issuing a bogus certificate to an imposter.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] It is also possible to register individuals and companies with the same or very similar names, which may lead to confusion.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] To minimize this hazard, the *certificate transparency* initiative proposes auditing all certificates in a public unforgeable log, which could help in the prevention of phishing.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In large-scale deployments, Alice may not be familiar with Bob's certificate authority (perhaps they each have a different CA server), so Bob's certificate may also include his CA's public key signed by a different CA2, which is presumably recognizable by Alice.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This process typically leads to a hierarchy or mesh of CAs and CA certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, which signals that it is no longer valid.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or misissued certificate until expiry.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Hence, revocation is an important part of a public key infrastructure.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Revocation is performed by the issuing CA, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] For distributing revocation information to clients, timeliness of the discovery of revocation (and hence the window for an attacker to exploit a compromised certificate) trades off against resource usage in querying revocation statuses and privacy concerns.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] If revocation information is unavailable (either due to accident or an attack), clients must decide whether to *fail-hard* and treat a certificate as if it is revoked (and so degrade availability) or to *fail-soft* and treat it as unrevoked (and allow attackers to sidestep revocation).
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Due to the cost of revocation checks and the availability impact from potentially-unreliable remote services, Web browsers limit the revocation checks they will perform, and will fail-soft where they do.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Certificate revocation lists are too bandwidth-costly for routine use, and the Online Certificate Status Protocol presents connection latency and privacy issues.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Other schemes have been proposed but have not yet been successfully deployed to enable fail-hard checking.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The CA/Browser Forum publishes the Baseline Requirements, a list of policies and technical requirements for CAs to follow.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] These are a requirement for inclusion in the certificate stores of Firefox and Safari.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] On April 14, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum passed a ballot to reduce SSL/TLS certificates to 47 day maximum term by March 15, 2029.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] If the CA can be subverted, then the security of the entire system is lost, potentially subverting all the entities that trust the compromised CA.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] For example, suppose an attacker, Eve, manages to get a CA to issue to her a certificate that claims to represent Alice.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] That is, the certificate would publicly state that it represents Alice, and might include other information about Alice.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Some of the information about Alice, such as her employer name, might be true, increasing the certificate's credibility.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Eve, however, would have the all-important private key associated with the certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Eve could then use the certificate to send a digitally signed email to Bob, tricking Bob into believing that the email was from Alice.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Bob might even respond with encrypted email, believing that it could only be read by Alice, when Eve is actually able to decrypt it using the private key.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] A notable case of CA subversion like this occurred in 2001, when the certificate authority VeriSign issued two certificates to a person claiming to represent Microsoft.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The certificates have the name "Microsoft Corporation", so they could be used to spoof someone into believing that updates to Microsoft software came from Microsoft when they actually did not.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Microsoft and VeriSign took steps to limit the impact of the problem.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In 2008, Comodo reseller Certstar sold a certificate for mozilla.com to Eddy Nigg, who had no authority to represent Mozilla.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In 2011 fraudulent certificates were obtained from Comodo and DigiNotar, allegedly by Iranian hackers.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] There is evidence that the fraudulent DigiNotar certificates were used in a man-in-the-middle attack in Iran.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In 2012, it became known that Trustwave issued a subordinate root certificate that was used for transparent traffic management (man-in-the-middle) which effectively permitted an enterprise to sniff SSL internal network traffic using the subordinate certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In 2012, the Flame malware (also known as SkyWiper) contained modules that had an MD5 collision with a valid certificate issued by a Microsoft Terminal Server licensing certificate that used the broken MD5 hash algorithm.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The authors thus was able to conduct a collision attack with the hash listed in the certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] In 2015, a Chinese certificate authority named MCS Holdings and affiliated with China's central domain registry issued unauthorized certificates for Google domains.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Google thus removed both MCS and the root certificate authority from Chrome and have revoked the certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] An attacker who steals a certificate authority's private keys is able to forge certificates as if they were CA, without needed ongoing access to the CA's systems.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Key theft is therefore one of the main risks certificate authorities defend against.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Publicly trusted CAs almost always store their keys on a hardware security module (HSM), which allows them to sign certificates with a key, but generally prevent extraction of that key with both physical and software controls.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] CAs typically take the further precaution of keeping the key for their long-term root certificates in an HSM that is kept offline, except when it is needed to sign shorter-lived intermediate certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The intermediate certificates, stored in an online HSM, can do the day-to-day work of signing end-entity certificates and keeping revocation information up to date.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] CAs sometimes use a key ceremony when generating signing keys, in order to ensure that the keys are not tampered with or copied.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The critical weakness in the way that the current X.509 scheme is implemented is that any CA trusted by a particular party can then issue certificates for any domain they choose.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Such certificates will be accepted as valid by the trusting party whether they are legitimate and authorized or not.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This is a serious shortcoming given that the most commonly encountered technology employing X.509 and trusted third parties is the HTTPS protocol.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] As all major web browsers are distributed to their end-users pre-configured with a list of trusted CAs that numbers in the dozens this means that any one of these pre-approved trusted CAs can issue a valid certificate for any domain whatsoever.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] The industry response to this has been muted.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] Given that the contents of a browser's pre-configured trusted CA list is determined independently by the party that is distributing or causing to be installed the browser application there is really nothing that the CAs themselves can do.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] This issue is the driving impetus behind the development of the DNS-based Authentication of Named Entities (DANE) protocol.
[src:azure-key-vault/certificate-authority] If adopted in conjunction with Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) DANE will greatly reduce if not eliminate the role of trusted third parties in a domain's PKI.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] In cryptography, **encryption** (more specifically, encoding) is the process of transforming information in a way that, ideally, only authorized parties can decode.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] This process converts the original representation of the information, known as plaintext, into an alternative form known as ciphertext.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Despite its goal, encryption does not itself prevent interference but denies the intelligible content to a would-be interceptor.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] For technical reasons, an encryption scheme usually uses a pseudo-random encryption key generated by an algorithm.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] It is possible to decrypt the message without possessing the key but, for a well-designed encryption scheme, considerable computational resources and skills are required.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] An authorized recipient can easily decrypt the message with the key provided by the originator to recipients but not to unauthorized users.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Historically, various forms of encryption have been used to aid in cryptography.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Early encryption techniques were often used in military messaging.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Since then, new techniques have emerged and become commonplace in all areas of modern computing.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Modern encryption schemes use the concepts of public-key and symmetric-key.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Modern encryption techniques ensure security because modern computers are inefficient at cracking the encryption.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] One of the earliest forms of encryption is symbol replacement, which was first found in the tomb of Khnumhotep II, who lived in 1900 BC Egypt.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Symbol replacement encryption is "non-standard," which means that the symbols require a cipher or key to understand.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] This type of early encryption was used throughout Ancient Greece and Rome for military purposes.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] One of the most famous military encryption developments was the Caesar cipher, in which a plaintext letter is shifted a fixed number of positions along the alphabet to get the encoded letter.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] A message encoded with this type of encryption could be decoded with a fixed number on the Caesar cipher.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Around 800 AD, Arab mathematician al-Kindi developed the technique of frequency analysis – which was an attempt to crack ciphers systematically, including the Caesar cipher.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] This technique looked at the frequency of letters in the encrypted message to determine the appropriate shift: for example, the most common letter in English text is E and is therefore likely to be represented by the letter that appears most commonly in the ciphertext.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] This technique was rendered ineffective by the polyalphabetic cipher, described by al-Qalqashandi (1355–1418) and Leon Battista Alberti (in 1465), which varied the substitution alphabet as encryption proceeded in order to confound such analysis.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Around 1790, Thomas Jefferson theorized a cipher to encode and decode messages to provide a more secure way of military correspondence.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The cipher, known today as the Wheel Cipher or the Jefferson Disk, although never actually built, was theorized as a spool that could jumble an English message up to 36 characters.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The message could be decrypted by plugging in the jumbled message to a receiver with an identical cipher.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] A similar device to the Jefferson Disk, the M-94, was developed in 1917 independently by US Army Major Joseph Mauborne.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] This device was used in U.S. military communications until 1942.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] In World War II, the Axis powers used a more advanced version of the M-94 called the Enigma Machine.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The Enigma Machine was more complex because unlike the Jefferson Wheel and the M-94, each day the jumble of letters switched to a completely new combination.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Each day's combination was only known by the Axis, so many thought the only way to break the code would be to try over 17,000 combinations within 24 hours.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The Allies used computing power to severely limit the number of reasonable combinations they needed to check every day, leading to the breaking of the Enigma Machine.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Today, encryption is used in the transfer of communication over the Internet for security and commerce.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] As computing power continues to increase, computer encryption is constantly evolving to prevent eavesdropping attacks.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] One of the first "modern" cipher suites, DES, used a 56-bit key with 72,057,594,037,927,936 possibilities; it was cracked in 1999 by EFF's brute-force DES cracker, which required 22 hours and 15 minutes to do so.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Modern encryption standards often use stronger key sizes, such as AES (256-bit mode), TwoFish, ChaCha20-Poly1305, Serpent (configurable up to 512-bit).
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Cipher suites that use a 128-bit or higher key, like AES, cannot be brute-forced because the total number of keys is 3.4028237e+38 possibilities.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The most likely option for cracking ciphers with large key sizes is to find vulnerabilities in the cipher itself, like inherent biases and backdoors or by exploiting physical side effects through Side-channel attacks.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] For example, RC4, a stream cipher, was cracked due to inherent biases and vulnerabilities in the cipher.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] In the context of cryptography, encryption serves as a mechanism to ensure confidentiality.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Since data may be visible on the Internet, sensitive information such as passwords and personal communication may be exposed to potential interceptors.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The process of encrypting and decrypting messages involves keys.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The two main types of keys in cryptographic systems are symmetric-key and public-key (also known as asymmetric-key).
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Many complex cryptographic algorithms often use simple modular arithmetic in their implementations.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] In symmetric-key schemes, the encryption and decryption keys are the same.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Communicating parties must have the same key in order to achieve secure communication.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The German Enigma Machine used a new symmetric-key each day for encoding and decoding messages.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] In public-key cryptography schemes, the encryption key is published for anyone to use and encrypt messages.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] However, only the receiving party has access to the decryption key that enables messages to be read.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Public-key encryption was first described in a secret document in 1973; beforehand, all encryption schemes were symmetric-key (also called private-key).
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Although published subsequently, the work of Diffie and Hellman was published in a journal with a large readership, and the value of the methodology was explicitly described.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The method became known as the Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] RSA (Rivest–Shamir–Adleman) is another notable public-key cryptosystem.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Created in 1978, it is still used today for applications involving digital signatures.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Using number theory, the RSA algorithm selects two prime numbers, which help generate both the encryption and decryption keys.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] A publicly available public-key encryption application called Pretty Good Privacy (PGP) was written in 1991 by Phil Zimmermann, and distributed free of charge with source code.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] PGP was purchased by Symantec in 2010 and is regularly updated.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Encryption has long been used by militaries and governments to facilitate secret communication.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] It is now commonly used in protecting information within many kinds of civilian systems.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] For example, the Computer Security Institute reported that in 2007, 71% of companies surveyed used encryption for some of their data in transit, and 53% used encryption for some of their data in storage.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Encryption can be used to protect data "at rest", such as information stored on computers and storage devices (e.g.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] In recent years, there have been numerous reports of confidential data, such as customers' personal records, being exposed through loss or theft of laptops or backup drives; encrypting such files at rest helps protect them if physical security measures fail.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Digital rights management systems, which prevent unauthorized use or reproduction of copyrighted material and protect software against reverse engineering (see also copy protection), is another somewhat different example of using encryption on data at rest.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Encryption is also used to protect data in transit, for example data being transferred via networks (e.g. the Internet, e-commerce), mobile telephones, wireless microphones, wireless intercom systems, Bluetooth devices and bank automatic teller machines.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] There have been numerous reports of data in transit being intercepted in recent years.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Data should also be encrypted when transmitted across networks in order to protect against eavesdropping of network traffic by unauthorized users.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Encryption plays a central role in meeting regulatory requirements for the protection of sensitive data.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Under the HIPAA Security Rule, encryption of electronic protected health information (ePHI) is classified as an "addressable" implementation specification, meaning covered entities must implement it or document why an equivalent alternative measure is reasonable and appropriate.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Notably, the HIPAA Breach Notification Rule provides a safe harbor for encrypted data: breaches involving ePHI that has been encrypted in accordance with NIST standards are not considered reportable breaches.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would make encryption of ePHI at rest and in transit a mandatory requirement, removing its current "addressable" status.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires encryption of cardholder data both in storage (Requirement 3) and during transmission over open public networks (Requirement 4), specifying the use of strong cryptographic algorithms.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Conventional methods for permanently deleting data from a storage device involve overwriting the device's whole content with zeros, ones, or other patterns – a process which can take a significant amount of time, depending on the capacity and the type of storage medium.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Cryptography offers a way of making the erasure almost instantaneous.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] An example implementation of this method can be found on iOS devices, where the cryptographic key is kept in a dedicated 'effaceable storage'.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Because the key is stored on the same device, this setup on its own does not offer full privacy or security protection if an unauthorized person gains physical access to the device.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Encryption is used in the 21st century to protect digital data and information systems.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] As computing power increased over the years, encryption technology has only become more advanced and secure.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] However, this advancement in technology has also exposed a potential limitation of today's encryption methods.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The length of the encryption key is an indicator of the strength of the encryption method.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] For example, the original encryption key, DES (Data Encryption Standard), was 56 bits, meaning it had 2^56 combination possibilities.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] With today's computing power, a 56-bit key is no longer secure, being vulnerable to brute force attacks.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Quantum computing uses properties of quantum mechanics in order to process large amounts of data simultaneously.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Quantum computing has been found to achieve computing speeds thousands of times faster than today's supercomputers.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] This computing power presents a challenge to today's encryption technology.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] For example, RSA encryption uses the multiplication of very large prime numbers to create a semiprime number for its public key.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Decoding this key without its private key requires this semiprime number to be factored, which can take a very long time to do with modern computers.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] It would take a supercomputer anywhere between weeks to months to factor in this key.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] However, quantum computing can use quantum algorithms to factor this semiprime number in the same amount of time it takes for normal computers to generate it.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] This would make all data protected by current public-key encryption vulnerable to quantum computing attacks.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Other encryption techniques like elliptic curve cryptography and symmetric key encryption are also vulnerable to quantum computing.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] While quantum computing could be a threat to encryption security in the future, quantum computing as it currently stands is still very limited.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Quantum computing currently is not commercially available, cannot handle large amounts of code, and only exists as computational devices, not computers.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Furthermore, quantum computing advancements will be able to be used in favor of encryption as well.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The National Security Agency (NSA) is currently preparing post-quantum encryption standards for the future.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Quantum encryption promises a level of security that will be able to counter the threat of quantum computing.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Encryption is an important tool but is not sufficient alone to ensure the security or privacy of sensitive information throughout its lifetime.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Most applications of encryption protect information only at rest or in transit, leaving sensitive data in clear text and potentially vulnerable to improper disclosure during processing, such as by a cloud service for example.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Homomorphic encryption and secure multi-party computation are emerging techniques to compute encrypted data; these techniques are general and Turing complete but incur high computational and/or communication costs.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] In response to encryption of data at rest, cyber-adversaries have developed new types of attacks.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] These more recent threats to encryption of data at rest include cryptographic attacks, stolen ciphertext attacks, attacks on encryption keys, insider attacks, data corruption or integrity attacks, data destruction attacks, and ransomware attacks.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Data fragmentation and active defense data protection technologies attempt to counter some of these attacks, by distributing, moving, or mutating ciphertext so it is more difficult to identify, steal, corrupt, or destroy.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The question of balancing the need for national security with the right to privacy has been debated for years, since encryption has become critical in today's digital society.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The modern encryption debate started around the '90s when US government tried to ban cryptography because, according to them, it would threaten national security.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The debate is polarized around two opposing views.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Those who see strong encryption as a problem making it easier for criminals to hide their illegal acts online and others who argue that encryption keep digital communications safe.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The debate heated up in 2014, when Big Tech like Apple and Google set encryption by default in their devices.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] This was the start of a series of controversies that puts governments, companies and internet users at stake.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Authenticated encryption algorithms are designed to provide both encryption and integrity protection together.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Standards for cryptographic software and hardware to perform encryption are widely available, but successfully using encryption to ensure security may be a challenging problem.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] A single error in system design or execution can allow successful attacks.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Sometimes an adversary can obtain unencrypted information without directly undoing the encryption.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] See for example traffic analysis, TEMPEST, or Trojan horse.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Encrypting at the time of creation is only secure if the encryption device itself has correct keys and has not been tampered with.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] If an endpoint device has been configured to trust a root certificate that an attacker controls, for example, then the attacker can both inspect and tamper with encrypted data by performing a man-in-the-middle attack anywhere along the message's path.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] The common practice of TLS interception by network operators represents a controlled and institutionally sanctioned form of such an attack, but countries have also attempted to employ such attacks as a form of control and censorship.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Even when encryption effectively conceals a message’s content and prevents tampering, the *length* of the ciphertext remains a form of metadata that can leak sensitive information.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] For instance, the well-known CRIME and BREACH attacks against HTTPS exploited information leakage through encrypted message length as a side-channel attack.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Traffic analysis more broadly refers to techniques that use metadata—such as message size and timing—to infer information about communication patterns.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Applying padding to a message before encryption can help obscure its true plaintext length, though this increases the ciphertext size and adds bandwidth overhead.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Padding may be applied randomly or deterministically, each approach involving different trade-offs.
[src:azure-key-vault/encryption] Encrypting and padding data to produce padded uniform random blobs (PURBs) ensures that the ciphertext reveals no metadata about the plaintext’s structure, leaking only asymptotically minimal $O(\log \log M)$ information through its length.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] A **hardware security module** (**HSM**) is a physical computing device that safeguards and manages secrets (most importantly digital keys), and performs encryption and decryption functions for digital signatures, strong authentication and other cryptographic functions.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] These modules traditionally come in the form of a plug-in card or an external device that attaches directly to a computer or network server.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] A hardware security module contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] HSMs may have features that provide tamper evidence such as visible signs of tampering or logging and alerting, or tamper resistance which makes tampering difficult without making the HSM inoperable, or tamper responsiveness such as deleting keys upon tamper detection.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Each module contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips to prevent tampering and bus probing, or a combination of chips in a module that is protected by the tamper evident, tamper resistant, or tamper responsive packaging.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] A vast majority of existing HSMs are designed mainly to manage secret keys.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Many HSM systems have means to securely back up the keys they handle outside of the HSM.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Keys may be backed up in wrapped form and stored on a computer disk or other media, or externally using a secure portable device like a smartcard or some other security token.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] HSMs are used for real time authorization and authentication in critical infrastructure thus are typically engineered to support standard high availability models including clustering, automated failover, and redundant field-replaceable components.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] A few of the HSMs available in the market have the capability to execute specially developed modules within the HSM's secure enclosure.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Such an ability is useful, for example, in cases where special algorithms or business logic has to be executed in a secured and controlled environment.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] The modules can be developed in native C language, .NET, Java, or other programming languages.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Although the highest level of FIPS 140 security certification attainable is Security Level 4, most of the HSMs have Level 3 certification.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] In the Common Criteria system the highest EAL (Evaluation Assurance Level) is EAL7; most of the HSMs have EAL4+ certification.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] When used in financial payments applications, the security of an HSM is often validated against the HSM requirements defined by the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] A hardware security module can be employed in any application that uses digital keys.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Typically, the keys would be of high value - meaning there would be a significant, negative impact to the owner of the key if it were compromised.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] HSMs are also deployed to manage transparent data encryption keys for databases and keys for storage devices such as disk or tape.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Some HSM systems are also hardware cryptographic accelerators.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] They usually cannot beat the performance of hardware-only solutions for symmetric key operations.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] However, with performance ranges from 1 to 10,000 1024-bit RSA signatures per second, HSMs can provide significant CPU offload for asymmetric key operations.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Since the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) is recommending the use of 2,048 bit RSA keys from year 2010, performance at longer key sizes has become more important.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] To address this issue, most HSMs now support elliptic curve cryptography (ECC), which delivers stronger encryption with shorter key lengths.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] In PKI environments, the HSMs may be used by certification authorities (CAs) and registration authorities (RAs) to generate, store, and handle asymmetric key pairs.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] On the other hand, device performance in a PKI environment is generally less important, in both online and offline operations, as Registration Authority procedures represent the performance bottleneck of the Infrastructure.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Specialized HSMs are used in the payment card industry.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] HSMs support both general-purpose functions and specialized functions required to process transactions and comply with industry standards.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] They normally do not feature a standard API.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] The major organizations that produce and maintain standards for HSMs on the banking market are the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council, ANS X9, and ISO.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Performance-critical applications that have to use HTTPS (SSL/TLS), can benefit from the use of an SSL Acceleration HSM by moving the RSA operations, which typically requires several large integer multiplications, from the host CPU to the HSM device.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Typical HSM devices can perform about 1 to 10,000 1024-bit RSA operations/second.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Some performance at longer key sizes is becoming increasingly important.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] An increasing number of registries use HSMs to store the key material that is used to sign large zonefiles.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] OpenDNSSEC is an open-source tool that manages signing DNS zone files.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] On January 27, 2007, ICANN and Verisign, with support from the U.S.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Department of Commerce, started deploying DNSSEC for DNS root zones.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Root signature details can be found on the Root DNSSEC's website.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Blockchain technology depends on cryptographic operations.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Safeguarding private keys is essential to maintain the security of blockchain processes that utilize asymmetric cryptography.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] The private keys are often stored in a cryptocurrency wallet like the hardware wallet in the image.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] The synergy between HSMs and blockchain is mentioned in several papers, emphasizing their role in securing private keys and verifying identity, e.g. in contexts such as blockchain-driven mobility solutions.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Automotive hardware security modules (HSMs) are embedded cryptographic coprocessors integrated into electronic control units (ECUs) to protect in-vehicle systems and communication buses against manipulation and misuse.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] They act as a hardware root of trust by securely generating and storing cryptographic keys and offloading security-critical operations such as secure boot, encryption, decryption, authentication and attestation.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] In modern ECU designs, HSMs are one of several hardware primitives that can underpin a hardware root of trust alongside secure elements, trusted platform modules (TPMs), one-time programmable (OTP) and read-only memories (ROM), and physical unclonable functions (PUFs).
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Their use provides dedicated hardware support for cryptographic operations, but also introduces trade-offs in die area, power consumption and latency, so they are typically integrated into mid- and high-end automotive domain controllers rather than the smallest microcontrollers.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Automotive HSMs are typically accompanied by dedicated firmware and software components that manage access to cryptographic services.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] These include HSM firmware, secure boot loaders, cryptographic libraries, and middleware that expose security services to the operating system and application software.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] In AUTOSAR-based systems, HSM firmware may interface with standardized service layers to provide cryptographic operations to applications.
[src:azure-key-vault/hardware-security-module] Commercial HSM firmware implementations are available from several automotive software vendors, often as components integrated into AUTOSAR platforms or OEM security frameworks.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:azure-key-vault/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] A **public key infrastructure** (**PKI**) is a set of roles, policies, hardware, software and procedures used to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key cryptography set-ups.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] In cryptography, a PKI is an arrangement that *binds* public keys with respective identities of entities (like people and organizations).
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] The binding is established through a process of registration and issuance of certificates at and by a certificate authority (CA).
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Depending on the assurance level of the binding, this may be carried out by an automated process or under human supervision.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] When done over a network, this requires using a secure certificate enrollment or certificate management protocol such as CMP.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] The PKI role that may be delegated by a CA to assure valid and correct registration is called a *registration authority* (RA).
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] An RA is responsible for accepting requests for digital certificates and authenticating the entity making the request.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] RAs, however, do not sign or issue certificates (i.e., an RA is delegated certain tasks on behalf of a CA)." While Microsoft may have referred to a subordinate CA as an RA, this is incorrect according to the X.509 PKI standards.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] RAs do not have the signing authority of a CA and only manage the vetting and provisioning of certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] In the case of Microsoft Standalone CAs, the function of RA does not exist since all of the procedures controlling the CA are based on the administration and access procedure associated with the system hosting the CA and the CA itself rather than Active Directory.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Most non-Microsoft commercial PKI solutions offer a stand-alone RA component.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] An entity must be uniquely identifiable within each CA domain on the basis of information about that entity.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] A third-party validation authority (VA) can provide this entity information on behalf of the CA.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] The X.509 standard defines the most commonly used format for public key certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] PKI provides "trust services" - in plain terms trusting the actions or outputs of entities, be they people or computers.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Trust service objectives respect one or more of the following capabilities: Confidentiality, Integrity and Authenticity (CIA).
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Public-key cryptography is a cryptographic technique that enables entities to securely communicate on an insecure public network, and reliably verify the identity of an entity via digital signatures.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] A public key infrastructure (PKI) is a system for the creation, storage, and distribution of digital certificates, which are used to verify that a particular public key belongs to a certain entity.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] The PKI creates digital certificates that map public keys to entities, securely stores these certificates in a central repository and revokes them if needed.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] The primary role of the CA is to digitally sign and publish the public key bound to a given user.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] This is done using the CA's own private key, so that trust in the user key relies on one's trust in the validity of the CA's key.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] When the CA is a third party separate from the user and the system, then it is called the Registration Authority (RA), which may or may not be separate from the CA.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] The key-to-user binding is established, depending on the level of assurance the binding has, by software or under human supervision.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] The term trusted third party (TTP) may also be used for certificate authority (CA).
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Moreover, PKI is itself often used as a synonym for a CA implementation.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or mis-issued certificate until expiry.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Revocation is performed by the issuing certificate authority, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] In this model of trust relationships, a CA is a trusted third party – trusted both by the subject (owner) of the certificate and by the party relying upon the certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Following major issues in how certificate issuing was managed, all major players gradually distrusted Symantec-issued certificates, starting in 2017 and completed in 2021.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] This approach involves a server that acts as an offline certificate authority within a single sign-on system.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] A single sign-on server will issue digital certificates into the client system, but never stores them.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Users can execute programs, etc. with the temporary certificate.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] It is common to find this solution variety with X.509-based certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Starting Sep 2020, TLS Certificate Validity reduced to 13 Months.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] An alternative approach to the problem of public authentication of public key information is the web-of-trust scheme, which uses self-signed certificates and third-party attestations of those certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] The singular term "web of trust" does not imply the existence of a single web of trust, or common point of trust, but rather one of any number of potentially disjoint "webs of trust".
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Examples of implementations of this approach are PGP (Pretty Good Privacy) and GnuPG (an implementation of OpenPGP, the standardized specification of PGP).
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Because PGP and implementations allow the use of e-mail digital signatures for self-publication of public key information, it is relatively easy to implement one's own web of trust.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] One of the benefits of the web of trust, such as in PGP, is that it can interoperate with a PKI CA fully trusted by all parties in a domain (such as an internal CA in a company) that is willing to guarantee certificates, as a trusted introducer.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] If the "web of trust" is completely trusted then, because of the nature of a web of trust, trusting one certificate is granting trust to all the certificates in that web.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] A PKI is only as valuable as the standards and practices that control the issuance of certificates and including PGP or a personally instituted web of trust could significantly degrade the trustworthiness of that enterprise's or domain's implementation of PKI.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Another alternative, which does not deal with public authentication of public key information, is the simple public key infrastructure (SPKI), which grew out of three independent efforts to overcome the complexities of X.509 and PGP's web of trust.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] SPKI does not associate users with persons, since the *key* is what is trusted, rather than the person.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] SPKI does not use any notion of trust, as the verifier is also the issuer.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] This is called an "authorization loop" in SPKI terminology, where authorization is integral to its design.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] This type of PKI is specially useful for making integrations of PKI that do not rely on third parties for certificate authorization, certificate information, etc.; a good example of this is an air-gapped network in an office.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Decentralized identifiers (DIDs) eliminate dependence on centralized registries for identifiers as well as centralized certificate authorities for key management, which is the standard in hierarchical PKI.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] In cases where the DID registry is a distributed ledger, each entity can serve as its own root authority.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] This architecture is referred to as decentralized PKI (DPKI).
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Developments in PKI occurred in the early 1970s at the British intelligence agency GCHQ, where James Ellis, Clifford Cocks and others made important discoveries related to encryption algorithms and key distribution.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Because developments at GCHQ are highly classified, the results of this work were kept secret and not publicly acknowledged until the mid-1990s.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] The public disclosure of both secure key exchange and asymmetric key algorithms in 1976 by Diffie, Hellman, Rivest, Shamir, and Adleman changed secure communications entirely.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Assorted cryptographic protocols were invented and analyzed within which the new cryptographic primitives could be effectively used.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] With the invention of the World Wide Web and its rapid spread, the need for authentication and secure communication became still more acute.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Commercial reasons alone (e.g., e-commerce, online access to proprietary databases from web browsers) were sufficient.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Taher Elgamal and others at Netscape developed the SSL protocol ('https' in Web URLs); it included key establishment, server authentication (prior to v3, one-way only), and so on.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] A PKI structure was thus created for Web users/sites wishing secure communications.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Vendors and entrepreneurs saw the possibility of a large market, started companies (or new projects at existing companies), and began to agitate for legal recognition and protection from liability.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Consumer groups raised questions about privacy, access, and liability considerations, which were more taken into consideration in some jurisdictions than in others.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] The enacted laws and regulations differed, and there were technical and operational problems in converting PKI schemes into successful commercial operation.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Progress has been much slower than pioneers had imagined it would be.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] By the first few years of the 21st century, the underlying cryptographic engineering was clearly not easy to deploy correctly.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Operating procedures (manual or automatic) were not easy to correctly design (nor even if so designed, to execute perfectly, which the engineering required).
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] The standards that existed were insufficient.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] PKI vendors have found a market, but it is not quite the market envisioned in the mid-1990s, and it has grown both more slowly and in somewhat different ways than were anticipated.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] PKIs have not solved some of the problems they were expected to, and several major vendors have gone out of business or been acquired by others.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] PKI has had the most success in government implementations; the largest PKI implementation to date is the Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) PKI infrastructure for the Common Access Cards program.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Some argue that purchasing certificates for securing websites by SSL/TLS and securing software by code signing is a costly venture for small businesses.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] However, the emergence of free alternatives, such as Let's Encrypt, has changed this.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] HTTP/2, the latest version of HTTP protocol, allows unsecured connections in theory; in practice, major browser companies have made it clear that they would support this protocol only over a PKI secured TLS connection.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Web browser implementation of HTTP/2 including Chrome, Firefox, Opera, and Edge supports HTTP/2 only over TLS by using the ALPN extension of the TLS protocol.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] This would mean that, to get the speed benefits of HTTP/2, website owners would be forced to purchase SSL/TLS certificates controlled by corporations.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Currently the majority of web browsers are shipped with pre-installed intermediate certificates issued and signed by a certificate authority, by public keys certified by so-called root certificates.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] This means browsers need to carry a large number of different certificate providers, increasing the risk of a key compromise.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] When a key is known to be compromised, it could be fixed by revoking the certificate, but such a compromise is not easily detectable and can be a huge security breach.
[src:azure-key-vault/public-key-infrastructure] Browsers have to issue a security patch to revoke intermediary certificates issued by a compromised root certificate authority.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] In one type of secret sharing scheme there is one *dealer* and *n* *players*.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The dealer gives a share of the secret to the players, but only when specific conditions are fulfilled will the players be able to reconstruct the secret from their shares.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The dealer accomplishes this by giving each player a share in such a way that any group of *t* (for *threshold*) or more players can together reconstruct the secret but no group of fewer than *t* players can.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Such a system is called a (*t*, *n*)-threshold scheme (sometimes it is written as an (*n*, *t*)-threshold scheme).
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing was invented independently by Adi Shamir and George Blakley in 1979.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes are ideal for storing information that is highly sensitive and highly important.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Examples include: encryption keys, missile launch codes, and numbered bank accounts.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Each of these pieces of information must be kept highly confidential, as their exposure could be disastrous; however, it is also critical that they should not be lost.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Traditional methods for encryption are ill-suited for simultaneously achieving high levels of confidentiality and reliability.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] This is because when storing the encryption key, one must choose between keeping a single copy of the key in one location for maximum secrecy, or keeping multiple copies of the key in different locations for greater reliability.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Increasing reliability of the key by storing multiple copies lowers confidentiality by creating additional attack vectors; there are more opportunities for a copy to fall into the wrong hands.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes address this problem, and allow arbitrarily high levels of confidentiality and reliability to be achieved.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing also allows the distributor of the secret to trust a group 'in aggregate'.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Traditionally, giving a secret to a group for safekeeping would require that the distributor completely trust all members of the group.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes allow the distributor to securely store the secret with the group even if not all members can be trusted all the time.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] So long as the number of traitors is never more than the critical number needed to reconstruct the secret, the secret is safe.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes are important in cloud computing environments.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Thus a key can be distributed over many servers by a threshold secret sharing mechanism.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The key is then reconstructed when needed.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing has also been suggested for sensor networks where the links are liable to be tapped, by sending the data in shares which makes the task of the eavesdropper harder.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The security in such environments can be made greater by continuous changing of the way the shares are constructed.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] A secure secret sharing scheme distributes shares so that anyone with fewer than *t* shares has no more information about the secret than someone with 0 shares.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Consider for example the secret sharing scheme in which the secret phrase "password" is divided into the shares "pa––––––", "––ss––––", "––––wo––", and "––––––rd".
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] A person with 0 shares knows only that the password consists of eight letters, and thus would have to guess the password from 268 = 208 billion possible combinations.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] A person with one share, however, would have to guess only the six letters, from 266 = 308 million combinations, and so on as more persons collude.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Consequently, this system is not a "secure" secret sharing scheme, because a player with fewer than *t* secret shares is able to reduce the problem of obtaining the inner secret without first needing to obtain all of the necessary shares.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] In contrast, consider the secret sharing scheme where *X* is the secret to be shared, *Pi* are public asymmetric encryption keys and *Qi* their corresponding private keys.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] In this scheme, any player with private key 1 can remove the outer layer of encryption, a player with keys 1 and 2 can remove the first and second layer, and so on.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] A player with fewer than *N* keys can never fully reach the secret *X* without first needing to decrypt a public-key-encrypted blob for which he does not have the corresponding private key – a problem that is currently believed to be computationally infeasible.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Additionally we can see that any user with all *N* private keys is able to decrypt all of the outer layers to obtain *X*, the secret, and consequently this system is a secure secret distribution system.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Several secret-sharing schemes are said to be information-theoretically secure and can be proven to be so, while others give up this *unconditional security* for improved efficiency while maintaining enough security to be considered as secure as other common cryptographic primitives.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] For example, they might allow secrets to be protected by shares with entropy of 128 bits each, since each share would be considered enough to stymie any conceivable present-day adversary, requiring a brute force attack of average size 2127.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Note: *n* is the total number of 'players', among whom the shares are distributed, and *t* is the minimum number of players required to reveal the secret.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Instead, (1) can be performed using the binary operation in any group.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] For example, take the cyclic group of integers with addition modulo 232, which corresponds to 32-bit integers with addition defined with the binary overflow being discarded.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The secret *s* can be partitioned into a vector of *M* 32-bit integers, which we call *v*secret.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Then (*n* − 1) of the players are each given a vector of *M* 32-bit integers that is drawn independently from a uniform probability distribution, with player *i* receiving *vi*.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The secret vector can then be recovered by summing across all the players' vectors.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The difficulty lies in creating schemes that are still secure, but do not require all *n* shares.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] When space efficiency is not a concern, trivial *t* = *n* schemes can be used to reveal a secret to any desired subsets of the players simply by applying the scheme for each subset.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] For example, to reveal a secret *s* to any two of the three players Alice, Bob and Carol, create three ( ${\binom {3}{2}}$ ) different *t* = *n* = 2 secret shares for *s*, giving the three sets of two shares to Alice and Bob, Alice and Carol, and Bob and Carol.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] For example, imagine that the board of directors of a company would like to protect their secret formula.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The president of the company should be able to access the formula when needed, but in an emergency any 3 of the 12 board members would be able to unlock the secret formula together.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] One of the ways this can be accomplished is by a secret-sharing scheme with *t* = 3 and *n* = 15, where 3 shares are given to the president, and one share is given to each board member.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] In the worst case, the increase is exponential.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] This has led to the search for schemes that allow secrets to be shared efficiently with a threshold of players.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] A ramp secret sharing scheme is a secret-sharing scheme with two thresholds: groups below the lower threshold learn no information about the secret, groups at or above the upper threshold can reconstruct it, and intermediate-size groups may obtain partial information.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] This relaxation can reduce the size of shares.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Hirosuke Yamamoto's (*k*, *L*, *n*) threshold scheme is an early information-theoretic formulation of this trade-off.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] In this scheme, any *t* out of *n* shares may be used to recover the secret.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The system relies on the idea that one can construct a unique polynomial of degree *t* − 1, such that each of the *t* points lies on the polynomial.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] It takes two points to define a straight line, three points to fully define a quadratic, four points to define a cubic curve, and so on.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] That is, it takes *t* points to define a polynomial of degree *t* − 1.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The method is to create a polynomial of degree *t* − 1 with the secret as the first coefficient and the remaining coefficients picked at random.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Next find *n* points on the curve and give one to each of the players.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] When at least *t* out of the *n* players reveal their points, there is sufficient information to fit a (*t* − 1)th degree polynomial to them, the first coefficient being the secret.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] , and the secret is the point at which three shares intersect.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Two nonparallel lines in the same plane intersect at exactly one point.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Three nonparallel planes in space intersect at exactly one point.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] More generally, any *n* nonparallel (*n* − 1)-dimensional hyperplanes intersect at a specific point.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The secret may be encoded as any single coordinate of the point of intersection.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] If the secret is encoded using all the coordinates, even if they are random, then an insider (someone in possession of one or more of the (*n* − 1)-dimensional hyperplanes) gains information about the secret since he knows it must lie on his plane.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] If an insider can gain any more knowledge about the secret than an outsider can, then the system no longer has information theoretic security.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] If only one of the *n* coordinates is used, then the insider knows no more than an outsider (i.e., that the secret must lie on the *x*-axis for a 2-dimensional system).
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Each player is given enough information to define a hyperplane; the secret is recovered by calculating the planes' point of intersection and then taking a specified coordinate of that intersection.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Blakley's scheme is less space-efficient than Shamir's; while Shamir's shares are each only as large as the original secret, Blakley's shares are *t* times larger, where *t* is the threshold number of players.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Blakley's scheme can be tightened by adding restrictions on which planes are usable as shares.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The resulting scheme is equivalent to Shamir's polynomial system.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The Chinese remainder theorem can also be used in secret sharing, for it provides us with a method to uniquely determine a number *S* modulo *k* many pairwise coprime integers $m_{1},m_{2},...,m_{k}$ , given that $S<\prod _{i=1}^{k}m_{i}$ .
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] There are two secret sharing schemes that make use of the Chinese remainder theorem, Mignotte's and Asmuth-Bloom's Schemes.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] They are threshold secret sharing schemes, in which the shares are generated by reduction modulo the integers $m_{i}$ , and the secret is recovered by essentially solving the system of congruences using the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] If the players store their shares on insecure computer servers, an attacker could crack in and steal the shares.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] If it is not practical to change the secret, the uncompromised (Shamir-style) shares can be renewed.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The dealer generates a new random polynomial with constant term zero and calculates for each remaining player a new ordered pair, where the x-coordinates of the old and new pairs are the same.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Each player then adds the old and new y-coordinates to each other and keeps the result as the new y-coordinate of the secret.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] All of the non-updated shares the attacker accumulated become useless.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] An attacker can only recover the secret if he can find enough other non-updated shares to reach the threshold.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] This situation should not happen because the players deleted their old shares.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Additionally, an attacker cannot recover any information about the original secret from the update files because they contain only random information.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The dealer can change the threshold number while distributing updates, but must always remain vigilant of players keeping expired shares.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] A player might lie about his own share to gain access to other shares.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] A *verifiable secret sharing* (VSS) scheme allows players to be certain that no other players are lying about the contents of their shares, up to a reasonable probability of error.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Such schemes cannot be computed conventionally; the players must collectively add and multiply numbers without any individual's knowing what exactly is being added and multiplied.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The disadvantage of unconditionally secure secret sharing schemes is that the storage and transmission of the shares requires an amount of storage and bandwidth resources equivalent to the size of the secret times the number of shares.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] If the size of the secret were significant, say 1 GB, and the number of shares were 10, then 10 GB of data must be stored by the shareholders.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Alternate techniques have been proposed for greatly increasing the efficiency of secret sharing schemes, by giving up the requirement of unconditional security.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] One of these techniques, known as *secret sharing made short*, combines Rabin's information dispersal algorithm (IDA) with Shamir's secret sharing.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Data is first encrypted with a randomly generated key, using a symmetric encryption algorithm.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Next this data is split into N pieces using Rabin's IDA.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] This IDA is configured with a threshold, in a manner similar to secret sharing schemes, but unlike secret sharing schemes the size of the resulting data grows by a factor of (number of fragments / threshold).
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] For example, if the threshold were 10, and the number of IDA-produced fragments were 15, the total size of all the fragments would be (15/10) or 1.5 times the size of the original input.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] In this case, this scheme is 10 times more efficient than if Shamir's scheme had been applied directly on the data.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The final step in secret sharing made short is to use Shamir secret sharing to produce shares of the randomly generated symmetric key (which is typically on the order of 16–32 bytes) and then give one share and one fragment to each shareholder.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] A related approach, known as AONT-RS, applies an All-or-nothing transform to the data as a pre-processing step to an IDA.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The All-or-nothing transform guarantees that any number of shares less than the threshold is insufficient to decrypt the data.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] An information-theoretically secure *k*-of-*n* secret-sharing scheme generates *n* shares, each of size at least that of the secret itself, leading to the total required storage being at least *n*-fold larger than the secret.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] In multi-secret sharing designed by Matthew K.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Franklin and Moti Yung, multiple points of the polynomial host secrets; the method was found useful in numerous applications from coding to multi-party computations.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] In space efficient secret sharing, devised by Abhishek Parakh and Subhash Kak, each share is roughly the size of the secret divided by *k* − 1.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] This scheme makes use of repeated polynomial interpolation and has potential applications in secure information dispersal on the Web and in sensor networks.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] This method is based on data partitioning involving the roots of a polynomial in finite field.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Some vulnerabilities of related *space efficient* secret sharing schemes were pointed out later.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] They show that a scheme based on interpolation method cannot be used to implement a (*k*, *n*) scheme when the *k* secrets to be distributed are inherently generated from a polynomial of degree less than *k* − 1, and the scheme does not work if all of the secrets to be shared are the same, etc.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] A secret-sharing scheme can secure a secret over multiple servers and remain recoverable despite multiple server failures.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] The dealer may act as several distinct participants, distributing the shares among the participants.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] This is one of the major concepts behind the Vanish computer project at the University of Washington, where a random key is used to encrypt data, and the key is distributed as a secret across several nodes in a P2P network.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] In order to decrypt the message, at least *t* nodes on the network must be accessible; the principle for this particular project being that the number of secret-sharing nodes on the network will decrease naturally over time, therefore causing the secret to eventually *vanish*.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] However, the network is vulnerable to a Sybil attack, thus making Vanish insecure.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Any shareholder who ever has enough information to decrypt the content at any point is able to take and store a copy of X.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Consequently, although tools and techniques such as Vanish can make data irrecoverable within their own system after a time, it is not possible to force the deletion of data once a malicious user has seen it.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] This is one of the leading conundrums of digital rights management.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] A dealer could send *t* shares, all of which are necessary to recover the original secret, to a single recipient.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] An attacker would have to intercept all *t* shares to recover the secret, a task which is more difficult than intercepting a single file, especially if the shares are sent using different media (e.g. some over the Internet, some mailed on CDs).
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] For large secrets, it may be more efficient to encrypt the secret and then distribute the key using secret sharing.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing is an important primitive in several protocols for secure multiparty computation.
[src:azure-key-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing can also be used for user authentication in a system.
